## 10. SMP - Security Manager Protocol {#smp}

### 10.1 Why Pairing is Needed {#pairing-needed}

BLE devices must pair before secure communication. Pairing creates shared secret keys (LTK - Long-Term Key) that both devices can later use to encrypt/authenticate.

---

### 10.2 Three Phases of Pairing {#pairing-phases}

#### Phase 1: Pairing Feature Exchange
Both devices advertise their pairing capabilities (IO capabilities, key distribution preferences).

#### Phase 2: Secret Key Agreement
Using ECDH or Out-of-Band methods, both devices derive shared secrets.

#### Phase 3: Key Distribution
Devices exchange long-term keys (LTK), identity keys (IRK), and connection signature resolving keys (CSRK).

---

### 10.3 IO Capabilities & Pairing Method Selection {#io-capabilities}

Based on device input/output capabilities, BLE selects the best pairing method:

| IO Capability | Pairing Method | Security |
|---|---|---|
| **Display only** | Passkey Display | Medium |
| **Display + Input** | Passkey Entry | Medium |
| **Keyboard only** | Passkey Entry | Medium |
| **No Input/Output** | Just Works | Low (no user interaction) |
| **Keyboard + Display** | Out-of-Band (OOB) | High (no passive eavesdropping) |

**Just Works** is "pairing by default" – no human confirmation needed.

---

### 10.4 LE Secure Connections {#le-secure}

BLE 4.2+ introduced **LE Secure Connections**, which use ECDH (Elliptic Curve Diffie-Hellman) instead of the older weaker key agreement.

---

### 10.5 Key Distribution {#key-distribution}

After pairing, devices exchange these keys:

| Key | Purpose |
|-----|---------|
| **LTK (Long-Term Key)** | Encryption key for future connections |
| **IRK (Identity Resolving Key)** | Decrypt random MAC addresses to identify devices |
| **CSRK (Connection Signature Resolving Key)** | Verify message authenticity (message integrity checking) |

---

## 11. BLE Profiles - Standard Use Cases {#ble-profiles}

### 11.1 What is a Profile {#what-profile}

A **Profile** is a standardized collection of services and characteristics for a specific use case (heart rate, weather station, fitness tracker, etc.).

**Example: Heart Rate Profile**

```
Heart Rate Service
├─ Heart Rate Characteristic (UUID: 0x2A37)
│  └─ Read, Notify
│  └─ CCCD Descriptor
├─ Body Sensor Location (UUID: 0x2A38)
│  └─ Read
└─ Heart Rate Control Point (UUID: 0x2A39)
   └─ Write
```

---

### 11.2 Heart Rate Profile {#heart-rate-profile}

A wearable device (like a fitness tracker) exposes heart rate data via:

- **Service:** Heart Rate
- **Characteristics:**
  - Heart Rate Measurement (notifiable, shows BPM)
  - Body Sensor Location (readable, shows placement on body)

---

### 11.3 Voice Streaming Over HID {#voice-streaming}

Modern BLE devices (e.g., hearing aids) stream audio voice using HID over BLE.

---

### 11.4 BLE Audio Codecs - ADPCM, mSBC, LC3 {#audio-codecs}

BLE supports multiple audio codecs for different quality/bandwidth tradeoffs:

| Codec | Bitrate | Bandwidth | Quality | Use Case |
|-------|---------|-----------|---------|----------|
| **ADPCM** | 64 kbps | – | Lower | Low-power, older BLE devices |
| **mSBC** | 64 kbps | – | Shorter (-sBm) | Voice calls, better than ADPCM |
| **LC3** | 32-160 kbps | Higher (–20dBm line of sight) | Highest | New LE Audio standard; future-proof |

---

### 11.5 mSBC for BLE Voice - Settings & Frame Format {#msbc-settings}

| Setting | Value | Notes |
|---------|-------|-------|
| **Frame Duration** | 7.5 ms, 10 ms | Shorter = lower latency, higher CPU |
| **Bitrate** | 64 kbps | Fixed for mSBC |
| **Sampling Rate** | 16 kHz | Voice quality |

---

### 11.6 LC3 for LE Audio - Settings & Frame Format {#lc3-settings}

| Setting | Value | Notes |
|---------|-------|-------|
| **Frame Duration** | 7.5 ms, 10 ms | – |
| **Bitrate** | 24-160 kbps | Configurable for quality vs. power tradeoff |
| **Sampling Rate** | 8-48 kHz | Up to CD quality (44.1 kHz) |

